07127nam a22007815i 9780226126517DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013032851  a9780226126517  a(DE-B1597)524209  a(OCoLC)875894726  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBF531b.S38 2014 4aBF531 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a152.409/04522300aScience and Emotions after 1945 :bA Transatlantic Perspective /ced. by Daniel M. Gross, Frank Biess. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (384 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tNTRODUCTION. Emotional Returns -- tPART ONE. Neuroscience -- t1. Humanists and the Experimental Study of Emotion -- t2. “Both of Us Disgusted in My Insula”: Mirror-Neuron Theory and Emotional Empathy -- t3. Emotion Science and the Heart of a Two-Cultures Problem -- tPART TWO. Medicine -- t4. What Is an Excitement? -- t5. The Science of Pain and Pleasure in the Shadow of the Holocaust -- t6. Oncomotions: Experience and Debates in West Germany and the United States after 1945 -- tPART THREE. Psychiatry -- t7. The Concept of Panic: Military Psychiatry and Emotional Preparation for Nuclear War in Postwar West Germany -- t8. Preventing the Inevitable: John Appel and the Problem of Psychiatric Casualties in the US Army during World War II -- t9. Feeling for the Protest Faster: How the Self-Starving Body Influences Social Movements and Global Medical Ethics -- tPART FOUR. Social Sciences -- t10. Across Different Cultures? Emotions in Science during the Early Twentieth Century -- t11. Decolonizing Emotions: The Management of Feeling in the New World Order -- t12. Passions, Preferences, and Animal Spirits: How Does Homo Oeconomicus Cope with Emotions? -- t13. The Transatlantic Element in the Sociology of Emotions -- t14. Feminist Theories and the Science of Emotion -- t15. Affect, Trauma, and Daily Life: Transatlantic Legal and Medical Responses to Bullying and Intimidation -- tCoda: Erasures; Writing History about Holocaust Trauma -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThrough the first half of the twentieth century, emotions were a legitimate object of scientific study across a variety of disciplines. After 1945, however, in the wake of Nazi irrationalism, emotions became increasingly marginalized and postwar rationalism took central stage. Emotion remained on the scene of scientific and popular study but largely at the fringes as a behavioral reflex, or as a concern of the private sphere. So why, by the 1960s, had the study of emotions returned to the forefront of academic investigation? In Science and Emotions after 1945, Frank Biess and Daniel M. Gross chronicle the curious resurgence of emotion studies and show that it was fueled by two very different sources: social movements of the 1960s and brain science. A central claim of the book is that the relatively recent neuroscientific study of emotion did not initiate – but instead consolidated – the emotional turn by clearing the ground for multidisciplinary work on the emotions. Science and Emotions after 1945 tells the story of this shift by looking closely at scientific disciplines in which the study of emotions has featured prominently, including medicine, psychiatry, neuroscience, and the social sciences, viewed in each case from a humanities perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAffective neurosciencexHistoryy20th century. 0aEmotionsxPsychological aspects. 0aPsychologyzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aPsychologyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ascience, emotions, affect theory, n